        "## 2. Key Analytical Insights & Conclusions\n",
        "\n",
        "### I. Subjective Visual Analysis vs. Objective Diagnostics\n",
        "Initial exploratory visualization suggested a cluster of three potential outliers on the upper-right quadrant of the regression plane (high lung function gains paired with minimal biomarker shifts). However, computing formal OLS influence diagnostics using Cook's Distance ($4/n = 0.080$) revealed a different mathematical reality. Only a single observation, patient **CF-337**, crossed the critical influence threshold ($\\text{Cook's D} = 0.225$).\n",
        "\n",
        "### II. The Mechanics of Leverage\n",
        "Patient CF-337 represents an extreme observation in predictor space, exhibiting a net sweat chloride drop of $-83.4$ mmol/L (exceeding 2.5 standard deviations from the operational mean of $-45.0$). In an Ordinary Least Squares framework, this extreme distance from the predictor mean grants the observation immense leverage, allowing it to single-handedly anchor and tilt the geometric trajectory of the regression line.\n",
        "\n",
        "### III. Methodological Implications for Clinical Portfolios\n",
        "Rather than committing the data-integrity error of arbitrarily deleting non-conforming data points to artificially inflate an $R^2$ value or match a population parameter ($\\rho = -0.25$), this project highlights the necessity of formal sensitivity analysis. In small-sample clinical pilot frameworks ($N=50$), a single anomalous high-leverage responder can fundamentally alter clinical conclusions.\n",
        "\n",
        "### IV. Post-Hoc Power Recommendations\n",
        "A final power evaluation confirms that a sample size of $N=50$ possesses only an estimated $43\\%$ statistical power to capture an underlying population effect of $\\rho = -0.25$, incurring a $57\\%$ probability of a Type II error (false negative). To reliably detect this weak biological correlation at a standard $80\\%$ power threshold, future experimental protocols must scale to a minimum sample size of $N=123$ patients."
